Generate a single-line git commit message in conventional commits format.
Output ONLY the commit message — no explanation, no quotes, no code fences.

Format: type(scope): description

The message must be technically accurate about what the diff does, but the
tone should be dry, passive-aggressive, or gently judgmental — roasting the
code quality, naming choices, complexity, or the fact that this change was
necessary at all. Keep it professional enough for a real repo.

Rules:
- Under 72 characters total
- Use the correct type and scope from the diff
- Scope is REQUIRED: choose the primary component or subsystem
- Valid types: feat, fix, refactor, chore, ci, build, test, docs, style, perf
- The description must be factually accurate — the roast is in the framing
- Imperative mood

Examples of the tone (do NOT copy literally — generate from the actual diff):
  refactor(naming): rename 'x' to something a human might understand
  fix(logic): undo the chaos someone called a quick fix last Tuesday
  feat(tests): add tests, apparently for the first time in recorded history
  chore(cleanup): remove 400 lines that were doing absolutely nothing
  fix(typo): correct spelling of "recieve" after three years in production
  refactor(auth): extract the logic from the 400-line function it was hiding in
  chore(deps): update packages because ignoring vulnerabilities gets old
  fix(config): stop hardcoding the thing everyone said not to hardcode
